Below are a few utility functions that will be used later during the analysis.

Utility functions

Below function f_qualitygroup is used to return the dataset after grouping by the grouping variable. Although we need only to group by quality as part of this analysis , we can use any variable passed as grouping_var and input_var

library(dplyr)
library(lazyeval)

f_qualitygroup <- function(data,grouping_var,input_var){

 data.quality_group<-data %>%
  group_by_(grouping_var) %>%
  summarise_(group_mean=interp(~mean(input_var),input_var=as.name(input_var)),
            group_median=interp(~median(input_var),input_var=as.name(input_var)),
            n=~n()
            )
 return (data.quality_group)

}

Function to draw scatterplot with a few options needed for the analysis. It includes the Linear regression plot as well as the mean as the hline

f_drawscatter <- function(dataset, x, y,  opts=NULL) {
  ggplot(dataset, aes_string(x = x, y = y)) +
   geom_jitter(alpha = 1/5) +
   geom_smooth(method = 'lm')+
    geom_hline(yintercept = mean(dataset[,y]),linetype='longdash',alpha=0.5,
               color="blue")
}

Function to draw scatterplot with similar options as the scatterplot.

f_drawbox <- function(dataset, x, y,  opts=NULL) {
  ggplot(dataset, aes_string(x = x, y = y)) +
   geom_boxplot(alpha = 1/5) +
   geom_smooth(method = 'lm')+
    geom_hline(yintercept = mean(dataset[,y]),linetype='longdash',alpha=0.5,
               color="blue")
}

There may be other factors affecting the score in case of these which shadowed alcohol quantity.

whiteWineData.quality_groups<-whiteWineData%>%

  ggtitle(" Distribution of Alcohol values across quality scores ")

grid.arrange(qual_den_fp2,qual_alc_fp2)

Final plot 2 Description:

  1. We can see from the density vs quality plot that the wines of high quality have low density compared to the ones of low score.
  2. From the alcohol plot , except for wines of score 3 and 4 , the trend quality score seemed to increase with increase in alcohol level. For 3 and 4 , the total.sulfur.dioxide and residual.sugar were very high which could have contributed to the low score.

Reflection:

From the entire analysis , we can see that Alcohol content and Density have good correlation with the quality score, alcohol being a positive and Density being negative. There are other factors like residual.sugar, total.sulfur.dixoide which also have a negative correlation with quality score. There was no clear proof that these variables are dependent on one another but they definitely contributed together towards the quality score. High values of alcohol , pH and low values of density ,total.sulfur.dixoide and residual.sugar seemed to have lead to better quality score.

Although there are trends , there are deviations which I could not explain with the given dataset. For e.g., Density and Alcohol have negative and positive correlation with Quality score in general but wines of Score 3 have greater alcohol content than wines of score 4 and 5. Similarly Wines of score 5 have greater Density than wines of score 3 and 4. I could not find a way to dig deeper to justify these anamolies.

The dataset had wines with quality scores 5 and 6 dominant.Hence we may not be able to use this as a training data to predict wines of very high quality. We may need more data that has details and composition of high quality wines.
